  <mainDescription>The Product Acceptance Plan details customer acceptance criteria, and identifies the product acceptance tasks (including&#xD;
identification of the test cases that need to be developed) that will be carried out, and assigned responsibilities and&#xD;
required resources. On a smaller scale project, this plan may be embedded within the Software Development Plan.</mainDescription>
  <purpose>&lt;a id=&quot;Top&quot; name=&quot;Top&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a id=&quot;XE_Product_Acceptance_Plan_document__as_artifact&quot;&#xD;
name=&quot;XE_Product_Acceptance_Plan_document__as_artifact&quot;>&lt;/a>&lt;a id=&quot;Purpose&quot; name=&quot;Purpose&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The purpose of the Product Acceptance Plan is to ensure that an objective and clearly-defined procedure, and a set of&#xD;
    criteria, will be used to determine whether the work products to be delivered to the customer are acceptable.&#xD;
&lt;/p></purpose>
  <representationOptions>&lt;a id=&quot;Tailoring&quot; name=&quot;Tailoring&quot;>&lt;/a> &#xD;
&lt;p>&#xD;
    The contract may be explicit about how the product is to be accepted, in which case there may be no need for a separate&#xD;
    plan. In projects that do not have a specific customer, the product may be deemed acceptable when it has achieved a&#xD;
    certain maturity (meantime between failure, for example). In that case, there is no acceptance separate from test and&#xD;
    usage, so you can dispense with this plan.&#xD;
&lt;/p>&lt;br />&#xD;
&lt;br /></representationOptions>
</org.eclipse.epf.uma:ArtifactDescription>
